r its key actors are not adults but schoolchildren. Lesley Sharp refutes dominant assumptions that African children are the helpless victims of postcolonial crises, incapable of organized, sustained collective thought or action.She insists instead on the political agency of Malagasy youth who, as they decipher their current predicament, offer potent, historicized critiques of colonial violence, nationalist resistance, foreign mass media, and schoolyard survival. Sharp asserts that autobiography and national history are inextricably linked and therefore must be read in tandem, a process that exposes how political consciousness is forged in the classroom, within the home, and on the street in Madagascar.Keywords: Critical pedagogy  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducationzMadagascar. 0aImperialism. 0aYouthxPolitical activityzMadagascar. 0aYouthzMadagascar. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafrica.  aautobiography.  acase study.  achildren.  aclassroom.  acollective memory.  acollective.  across cultural.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  aeducation.  aethnography.  ahistorical conscious.  ahistorical consciousness.  aidentity politics.  aidentity.  amadagascar.  amass media.  amemory.  anational history.  anationalist.  apolitical consciousness.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apostcolonial.  aschool.  asocial history.  asocial studies.  avictims.  aviolence.  ayouth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022950140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093588440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520935884423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520935884/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of Ca